{{icelandic name|Gunnar|male}}
'''Gunnar Þór Gíslason''' is an [[Iceland]]ic businessman who was the [[chairman]] of [[Stoke City F.C.]] between November 1999 and May 2006. At the time he was the youngest chairman in [[the Football League]].

==Chairman of Stoke City==
In November 1999 Gunnar Þór Gíslason led an Icelandic consortium of businessman to take over English football club [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] from [[Peter Coates]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gunnar Thor Gislason, Chairman|url=http://www.sagacapital.is/en/about-saga/shareholders-and-administration/board-of-directors|work=saga|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> He appointed his own choice of manager, [[Guðjón Þórðarson]] who led to club to the Division One in 2002. But he was sacked by Gíslason after a contract dispute.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stoke sack Thordarson|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stoke_city/1987271.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> [[Steve Cotterill]] was appointed but quickly left and [[Tony Pulis]] was given the role to keep Stoke in the second tier. He succeeded but after a poor [[2004–05 Stoke City F.C. season|2004–05 season]] Pulis was sacked for "failing to exploit the foreign transfer market" and in his place came Dutch manager [[Johan Boskamp]]. He was in charge for just a season and in May 2006 Gíslason resigned as chairman of Stoke City, selling control of the club back to Peter Coates who re-appointed Tony Pulis.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stoke_city/5004658.stm 'Chairman Gislason departs Stoke', BBC Sport, 22 May 2006]</ref>

